{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521905"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:38:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:38:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13767"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13767"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.95,0,0.02,0,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48944"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6386"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13767"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33944"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2363"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12591"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48944"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic for a routine health check. She has no specific complaints. Her medical history includes hypertension treated with perindopril. She does not take any other regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Pale yellow, slightly thickened plaques are noted on the medial aspects of her upper and lower eyelids bilaterally (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Xanthelasma","Syringoma","Sebaceous hyperplasia","Molluscum contagiosum","Seborrheic keratosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pale yellow plaques on the medial eyelids are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Exanthelasma\u003C/strong\u003E. Xanthelasma are cholesterol deposits that accumulate in macrophages in the superficial dermis, leading to the formation of yellowish papules and plaques, most commonly in the periorbital region. They are usually asymptomatic, and can vary in appearance being nodular or flat, soft or semisolid or singular or multiple symmetrical lesions.. While often idiopathic, xanthelasma can be associated with dyslipidemia, thyroid dysfunction and diabetes mellitus, so this incidental finding should prompt screening for hyperlipidemia and assessment of cardiovascular risk factors.  Lifestyle management should be discussed and the lesions may be removed by excision, laser therapy or cryotherapy however they may reoccur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESyringomas\u003C/strong\u003E are benign eccrine sweat duct tumors that present as small skin-colored to yellowish papules, often in the periorbital area. However, they tend to be firmer and more translucent than xanthelasma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESebaceous hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E appears as small yellowish papules on the face, representing enlarged sebaceous glands. However, they are not typically found in the periorbital region and have a central dell or depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMolluscum contagiosum\u003C/strong\u003E are small, firm, dome-shaped white, pink or flesh-coloured papules caused by a poxvirus. They often have a central umbilication and are more common in children or immunocompetent patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeborrheic keratosis\u003C/strong\u003E are waxy, pigmented \u0027stuck on\u0027 lesions which occur more commonly with eldery patients.  It may be lobulated or pedunculated on an eyelid and they are benign lesions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Xanthelasma are associated with hyperlipidemia and should prompt screening for dyslipidemia and cardiovascular risk factors.","Xanthelasma are usually a clinical diagnosis based on their characteristic appearance and location."],"references":["Nair PA, Singhal R. Xanthelasma palpebrarum - a brief review. Clinical Cosmetic Investigation Dermatology. 2017 Dec 18;11:1-5. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5739544/","Sun M, Huang S, Huilgol S, Selva D. Eyelid lesions in general practice. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2019:48(8). Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/august/eyelid-lesions-in-general-practice"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33944"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13767"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20710"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20710"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ykv1MfeoUJiuYuh3Vjs7J6KXprTnM5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ykv1MfeoUJiuYuh3Vjs7J6KXprTnM5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33944"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T15:32:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T13:53:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6386"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48944"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positi